To determine the regularity of the ideal \( I = (x^3 + y^3) \) in both \( k[x, y] \) and \( k[x, y, z] \), you can use the \texttt{regularity} function in Macaulay2. The regularity is related to the Betti diagram of the corresponding ideal. Given this is a specific ideal, you would expect it to have certain properties that can be computed directly.

Here’s how you would compute it in Macaulay2:

```macaulay2
R = QQ[x, y];
I = ideal(x^3 + y^3);
regI = regularity I;

R2 = QQ[x, y, z];
I2 = ideal(x^3 + y^3);
regI2 = regularity I2;
```

This will give you the Castelnuovo-Mumford regularity for the ideal in both polynomial rings. If you want to further investigate the underlying structure and calculate weights, you might want to consult the documentation on Betti diagrams or heft vectors.

To compute the Krull dimension of an arbitrary ring in `k[x, y, z]`, you can use the `dim` function in Macaulay2. Here's an example:

```macaulay2
R = QQ[x, y, z];
I = ideal(x^2 + y^2 - z^2);
krullDimension = dim R/I;
```
This code sets up the polynomial ring over the rationals `QQ` in the variables `x`, `y`, and `z`, defines an ideal, and then computes the Krull dimension of the quotient ring `R/I`. You can replace the ideal with any appropriate one for different calculations.
